The net present value refers to the comparison between the initial investment and the present value of the cash flow at the required rate of return. For this problem, we will solve for the number of transactions needed to make the system viable. To do this, we must first recall the formula for the net present value (NPV):

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{NPV}&=\text{Present value of system}-\text{Present value of costs}
\end{aligned}$$

From this formula, we will be able to solve for the average number of payments per day that will make this system viable.

However, in order to do that, we must first expand the formula for the net present value by defining the formula for the two parameters separately.

The present value of the system is given using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Present value of system}&=(\text{Ave. value of payment}\times\text{Ave. no of payments per day})\\
&\times \text{Reduced time}
\end{aligned}$$

For the present value of costs, the formula is:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Present value of costs}&=\dfrac{\text{Ave. no. of payments per day} \times \text{Variable lockbox fee}}{\text{Interest rate}/\text{No. of days}}\\
&+\dfrac{\text{Fixed annual cost}}{\text{Interest rate}}
\end{aligned}$$
